'''Ren<U+00E9> Pottier''' (born [[June 5]], [[1879]] in [[Moret-sur-Loing]] &ndash; died [[January 25]], [[1907]] in [[Levallois-Perret]]) was a [[France|French]] [[racing cyclist]] 

Pottier took first place in the [[Bordeaux-Paris]] 1903 race before turning professional. He came second in [[Paris-Roubaix]] 1905 and the [[Bordeaux-Paris]] race of 1905, then third in 1906<U+2019>s Paris-Roubaix race, before winning the [[Tour de France]] in 1906.

He was considered to be the finest climber of the Tour de France. In [[1905 Tour de France|the 1905 race]] he won the second stage, racing up the [[Ballon d<U+2019>Alsace]] climb in record speed to take the overall lead. However, on the next day's stage to [[Grenoble]] injuries from a crash on stage 1 and the previous day's exertions caught up with him and he abandoned.

The following year he returned to the [[1906 Tour de France|Tour]], clinching five stage victories and taking the overall victory. 

In September 1906 he won the [[Bol d'Or cycle race|Bol d'Or 24 hour cycle race]] at the [[V<U+00E9>lodrome Buffalo]] in [[Paris]] with a distance of 925.290 kilometres.

On [[January 25]] [[1907]] he committed [[suicide]] by [[hanging]] himself after having his heart broken. A few weeks later, [[Henri Desgrange]], patron of the Tour, erected a [[stele]] in his memory at the top of the [[Ballon d'Alsace]], a summit in the region of [[Alsace]] 

== Tour de France results==
*[[1905 Tour de France]]: Abandoned after the 3rd stage 
*[[1906 Tour de France]]: Overall winner and winner of 5 stages

